or all `n`, `myAdd n (succ m) = myAdd' n (succ m)`.\n   - By definition, `myAdd n (succ m) = succ (myAdd n m)` and `myAdd' n (succ m) = succ (myAdd' n m)`.\n   - By the inductive hypothesis, `myAdd n m = myAdd' n m`, so `succ (myAdd n m) = succ (myAdd' n m)`, which means `myAdd n (succ m) = myAdd' n (succ m)`.\n\nTherefore, by induction, for all `n m`, `myAdd n m = myAdd' n m`, which means the functions are extensionally equal. \n\nBut in Lean, to show that `myAdd = myAdd'`, it suffices to show that for all `n m`, they are equal. \n\nAlternatively, since Lean's `Function.funext_iff` says that two functions are equal if they are equal on all inputs, we can use this fact. \n\nBut in Lean,",
